Your job is to consider a number theory problem, and leave a plan for the next person to solve it. The problem will be revealed one sentence at a time. You do not have the entire problem yet, thus just do whatever calcluations/planning you think will be useful for the next person. If you don't think you can make any progress, say so. There may be errors in the provided work that was previously done and left for you, so check and fix them if necessary.
A school has between 150 and 200 students enrolled.Every afternoon, all the students come together to participate in gym class.The students are separated into six distinct sections of students.
Common factors of 150 and 200: 1, 2, 5, 10, 25, 50. It seems like the common factors between the number of students at the school may not directly help us with the problem of finding out how many students participate in gym class, as these factors are quite common among different numbers. 

Next step: Since the common factors do not provide a clear answer, let's think about the problem statement again and see if there are any other approaches we can take to determine the number of students in gym class each afternoon. Think about how many students might be in each class, if there are multiple classes, or any other factors that may impact the total number of students participating.
solution:
If there are $s$ students, then $s-1$ must be divisible by 6. In other words, we want to find the sum of all values of $s$ for which $s-1\equiv 0\pmod{6}$. The multiples of 6 in the given range are 150, 156, ..., 198, so the possible values of $s$ are 151, 157, ..., 199. Recalling that the sum of an arithmetic series is  \[
\frac{(\text{first term}+\text{last term})(\text{number of terms})}{2},
\]we find that these integers sum to $(151+199)(9)/2=\boxed{1575}$.
